Team Project Deliverable 1

The dataset that we have selected consists of data given by Airbnb to describe many of their locations in Madrid. In the original file, there are in total 106 variables and 20837 observations, from which some of the variables are mostly incomplete or require some data imputation.

The data that we have selected is located in the following link to the kaggle project Madrid AirBnB Data

The report will be divided into 4 main steps:

  1. Data Pre-Processing
    • Visualization of missing values
    • Dropping useless variables (url, has_image etc..)
    • Imputing missing data
    • Selecting quantitative variables for analysis
  2. Data Visualization
    • ScatterPlot Matrix
    • Parallel Lines Plots
    • Andrew’s Plot
    • Division between Groups
    • Kernel Densities/Histograms
  3. Data Metrics
    • Mean Vector
    • Covariance matrix
    • Correlation Matrix
    • Analysis of different groups
    • Shrinkage and standardization of variables
  4. Principal and Independent Component Analysis
    • Performing PCA
      • Analyse different groups
      • See which grouping criterion has the most difference
    • Performing ICA

Data Pre-Processing

In this step, we will first focus on variables that have a high percentage of missing data (\(>30%\)) these variables are of no use, and we cannot perform any analysis with them, therefore we need to drop them from the dataset.

Then, there exist some other variables that have no meaning or add nothing different to the analysis, like host, listing URL, images city, country, state and other variables. We need to drop these variables as well.

We present below a graph with the percentages of missing values per variable from the complete and original dataset downloaded from Kaggle.

So, after verification, we can drop the following variables that have many empty (NA) values, and therefore cannot be imputed.

dropVariables <- c("xl_picture_url", "thumbnail_url", "jurisdiction_names", "square_feet", "monthly_price", "weekly_price", "license", "notes", "access", "host_about", "house_rules", "transit",  "neighborhood_overview", "security_deposit", "space", "medium_url", "interaction")

X_usefulvar <- X[ , !(names(X) %in% dropVariables)]

But we still need to drop many variables that have no use for the analysis, for example: strings like description, experiences, picture urls and host urls.

dropUseless <- c("scrape_id","listing_url","last_scraped","name","summary","description","experiences_offered","picture_url", "host_id", "host_url", "host_name", "host_since", "host_location", "host_acceptance_rate", "host_thumbnail_url", "host_picture_url", "host_neighbourhood", "host_listings_count", "host_verifications", "street", "neighbourhood", "city", "state", "market", "smart_location", "country_code", "country", "is_location_exact", "amenities", "minimum_minimum_nights","maximum_minimum_nights", "minimum_maximum_nights", "maximum_maximum_nights", "minimum_nights_avg_ntm", "maximum_nights_avg_ntm", "calendar_updated", "has_availability", "calendar_last_scraped", "number_of_reviews_ltm", "requires_license", "require_guest_profile_picture", "calculated_host_listings_count", "calculated_host_listings_count_entire_homes", "calculated_host_listings_count_private_rooms", "calculated_host_listings_count_shared_rooms")

X_clean <- X_usefulvar[ , !names(X_usefulvar) %in% dropUseless]
length(X_clean)
## [1] 44

After dropping all the useless variables we stay with a more significant set of variables, note that we have not done any analysis yet, only dropping variables that are of no use for further tests. We must then select the set of quantitiative variables plus a few qualitative ones that we are going to make plots with for visualization and furhter statistical analysis.

Possible Categorical variables to consider:

  • Neighborhood
  • Host is superhost
  • property type / room type
  • instant_bookable Must include the selected variables in the dataset after doing the imputation of missing data
X_clean_quant = X_clean[, names(X_clean) %in% c("cleaning_fee","review_scores_value", "review_scores_location","review_scores_checkin","review_scores_accuracy","review_scores_ratin","review_scores_cleanliness","review_scores_communication","reviews_per_month","beds","host_total_listings_count","host_response_rate", "bathrooms","bedrooms","price","number_of_reviews","minimum_nights","maximum_nights","guests_included","extra_people","availability_30","availability_60","availability_90","availability_365","accommodates")]
gg_miss_var(X_clean_quant, show_pct = TRUE) + labs(title = "Percentage of missing values in the cleaned Dataset")

Now we have a cleaner dataset “X_clean_quant” to continue with the analysis. But as shown above, some of the variables have still some missing values (but in lower precentages now). These variables are: Cleaning fee, and the variables consisting of reviews for the locations.

Now is when one of the main steps of data pre-processing comes into play, performing data imputation. Adding values for the missing cells is very important, since we do not want to have NA’s in the PCA nor the ICA process.

library(mice)
## 
## Attaching package: 'mice'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     cbind, rbind
X_clean_quant$host_response_rate <- as.numeric(X_clean_quant$host_response_rate)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
X_clean_quant$price <- as.numeric(X_clean_quant$price)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
X_clean_quant$cleaning_fee <- as.numeric(X_clean_quant$cleaning_fee)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
X_clean_quant$extra_people <- as.numeric(X_clean_quant$extra_people)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
imputed_data  <-mice(X_clean_quant, m=3, meth='pmm', seed = 68)
## Warning: Number of logged events: 4
full_data <- complete(imputed_data)

n_miss <- apply(is.na(full_data),1,sum)
table(n_miss)
obs_miss_1 <- which(n_miss==1)
length <- length(X_clean_quant)
obs <- nrow(X_clean_quant)
